close_symbols: Build-time feature/configuration macros that enable/disable object types or make implementations no-ops (e.g. any OS_INCLUDE_* or implementation selection macros)
explanation:
To decide whether any part of OS_API_Impl_Init is dead code (i.e. can be removed without changing program behaviour) the analyzer needs the following symbols and why:

- OS_SUCCESS: value used for the early-return check; needed to know what constitutes success and whether the initial TableMutex call always/never returns this value.
- int32: the return type definition and its semantics (range/ABI) to interpret return values and comparisons.
- osal_objtype_t and each OS_OBJECT_TYPE_* enumerator listed in the switch (OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TASK, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_QUEUE, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_BINSEM, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_COUNTSEM, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_MUTEX, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_MODULE, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TIMEBASE, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_STREAM, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_DIR, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_FILESYS, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_CONDVAR): required to determine the complete set of possible idtype values, whether some case labels are aliases/duplicates, and whether some cases are unreachable at runtime.
- OS_Posix_TableMutex_Init: this function is called before the switch and its return can short-circuit the remainder of the function; you must know whether it can fail and whether it has side effects (global state) so that removing later calls would or would not change behaviour.
- Each OS_Posix_*_API_Impl_Init called in the switch (Task, Queue, BinSem, CountSem, Mutex, Module, TimeBase, Stream, Dir, FileSys, CondVar): you must know for each whether it has observable side effects (initialization of global state, hardware, time-dependent behaviour, registration, I/O) or whether it is a no-op/stub. If a function is non-empty or has side effects, its invocation is not dead. If it is a noop in all build configurations, the call could be dead.
- OS_Posix_GetSchedulerParams: transitively called by OS_Posix_TaskAPI_Impl_Init (per the call graph); needed to understand side effects of the Task init path.
- Build-time feature/configuration macros that enable/disable object types or alter implementations (generic placeholder for any OS_INCLUDE_*, OSAL_* or platform-selection macros): some implementations may be compiled out or become no-ops depending on configuration. These macros determine whether a case's call is actually executed/required in the deployed build.

With these symbols (type/enum definitions, the success constant, the TableMutex behavior, each per-object Init's implementation/side-effects and relevant build-time macros), an analyzer can determine whether any of the switch cases or the initial call are removable without changing program behaviour, and thus whether the function contains dead code.
